[2] Cholera - Guinea
Date: Sun, 20 Aug 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Scientific American [edited]
<http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?chanID=sa003&articleID=E1CD50F4A9880333CDAD4A24EE9D550C>

A cholera outbreak has killed at least 143 people in Guinea so far in 2006
but the death rate has slowed since Jun 2006, a UN report showed on Sun, 20
Aug 2006. An outbreak in 2005 killed more than 800 people across several
countries in the region, and has continued in southern Guinea.
"The epidemic which has hit the country since Apr 2005 remains of concern.
From Jan to Jul 2006, the Public Health Ministry has notified 1623 cases
of whom 143 died," the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian
Affairs said in a report.
The death toll was a significant increase on the 60 reported dead by late
Apr 2006, although the mortality rate has slowed, dropping to 5 deaths out
of 134 [3.7 percent - Mod.LL] cases in Jul 2006 from 9 dead out of 412
[2.2 percent - Mod.LL] in Jun 2006, it said.
The outbreak has hit the southern town of Gueckedou worst.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of Guinea can be found at:
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/guinea.pdf>. Gueckedou is
in the southeastern province of Guinee Forestiere. - Mod.LL]
